  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "From our trajectory plan above, we can see that our rocket will start in Earth's orbit, exit Earth's orbit, reach Mars' orbit and remain in that orbit. This path follows an elliptical shape - it is called a \"Hohmann Transfer Orbit\" or simply a \"Transfer Orbit\".\n",
    "\n",
    "The drawing below illustrates this trajectory:\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, let's figure out how to launch our satellite so that it follows this path!\n",
    "\n",
    "During our earlier training in Mission 2 (Rocket Launch Practice), we saw that leaving Earth's atmosphere requires a certain speed. In order to leave Earth's atmosphere *and* get to Mars, we need to go even faster!\n",
    "\n",
    "We need to determine the speed we need to leave Earth's atmosphere and start our elliptical trajectory. We also need to determine the speed that we need to slow down to, once we arrive at Mars' orbit - otherwise, we will be launched too far out into space!"
   ]
  },
